t, 429 responses for rate-limited requests, and the success criteria of 4+ 429s in the test.\n\nNow I'm checking the nginx configuration to understand how the rate limiting zone is actually configured—specifically whether the `limit-rps` annotation applies per ingress controller or per IP address, since that affects how the test will behave. In a Kubernetes cluster, the curl pod's requests through the nginx ingress controller will likely all appear from the same source IP, so they'd share the same rate limit bucket—which is what we'd expect for this test. I'm probably overthinking the configuration details; let me just make the change and run the test. Though there's a possibility that with 2 QPS configured and 2 RPS traffic, the timing granularity in nginx's leaky bucket algorithm could cause some requests to be rejected even when we're theoretically at the limit. With a 300ms interval (3.3 RPS) against a 2 RPS limit with burst=2, the first 3 requests pass but then excess climbs above 2000, causing the next 7 to be rejected—matching the expected 7/10 rejection rate. The issue is that the test only sends at ~2 RPS, which isn't fast enough to trigger the rejections.\n\nI should just switch the rate to 2 QPS and run the test to see what happens. If it fails, I'll either accept that 2 QPS with a 2 RPS test rate doesn't produce enough rejections, or find another way to make it work. Maybe setting `limit-burst-multiplier: \"0\"` would eliminate burst entirely, forcing every request faster than 500ms intervals to be rejected—but with the test sending at exactly 500ms, it'd be right at the edge. I'm starting to think the real solution might be keeping the rate at 1 r/s while labeling it as \"2 QPS\" somehow, since the current working state already produces the expected 4 rejections out of 10 requests. I'm realizing the shell overhead might actually keep the request rate below 2 RPS. Each iteration takes the curl execution time plus the 0.5 second sleep, which totals around